benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/catalog - Delete all versions for a per tenant catalog

covered: Valid Deletion flows (TC01, TC02, TC08, TC15) demonstrate successful deletions (204) of all catalog versions for a tenant under different header conditions and with a request body ignored.

Authorization and header validation (TC03, TC04, TC07, TC11, TC14) cover missing header, invalid token, malformed header values, header injection attempts, and partial header scenarios, returning 400/401/422 as appropriate and preventing deletion.
Non-Existent Resource or No Data scenarios (TC06 and TC05) verify 404 when tenant not found and 204 when there are no catalog versions, ensuring no deletion occurs in these cases.
System and Data Integrity Errors (TC09 and TC12) verify proper 500 responses on service failures and that deletions do not leave orphaned references, maintaining data integrity.
Concurrency handling (TC13) ensures correct behavior under concurrent delete requests and system consistency.
Edge Case Handling (TC08) shows that extra headers do not break the operation (deletion succeeds).
Performance considerations (TC10) verify deletion completes within a time threshold for large catalogs.
gaps: Soft Deletes semantics are not validated (hard delete vs soft delete).
Rate limiting/throttling tests are missing for delete operations.
Caching behavior (ETag/Cache-Control) for delete responses is not tested.
Auditing/logging verification for deletions is not covered.
recommendations: Add tests to verify whether deletions are hard or soft and check for corresponding audit trails/log entries if applicable.
Introduce rate-limiting tests to validate graceful degradation under burst DELETE load.
Add tests to validate caching headers and ETag semantics on DELETE responses if supported by the API.
Include more explicit tests around 404/204 mappings for non-existent tenants and catalog data, ensuring consistent messaging and behavior.
Consider additional tests for performance with even larger datasets and stricter time thresholds (e.g., < 2 seconds).
